# PR Debate Flow (Human-in-the-Loop)

## The Full Workflow

```
1. You ask Claude to implement something
2. Claude makes changes, shows them to you
3. Claude asks: "Shall I create a PR?" → you review locally first
4. PR is created → CI runs reviewer → posts inline comments on GitHub
5. You open Cursor → run /debate → Claude proposes a response plan
6. You review the plan and approve, modify, or reject each item
7. On approval → Claude posts replies + applies fixes + pushes
8. CI runs reviewer again on the new push → back to step 5
9. Repeat until you merge
```

## Step 5: How to Start the Debate

When the user asks to debate/respond to review comments, follow these steps IN ORDER. Do not skip to execution.

### Phase A — Fetch live comment state

```bash
PR=$(gh pr view --json number --jq .number)
REPO=ykita0224-work/hive-strategy

# All reviewer comments (top-level, not replies)
gh api repos/$REPO/pulls/$PR/comments \
  --jq '[.[] | select(.in_reply_to_id == null) | {id: .id, path: .path, line: .line, severity: (.body | split("**")[1] // ""), body: .body}]'

# Existing replies (already debated comments)
gh api repos/$REPO/pulls/$PR/comments \
  --jq '[.[] | select(.in_reply_to_id != null) | {reply_to: .in_reply_to_id, body: .body[:80]}]'
```

Only process comments that have NOT already been replied to.

### Phase B — Read the actual code

For each comment, read the full file at the referenced path before forming an opinion:
```bash
cat <path>
```
Do NOT rely on the diff alone — read the full file context.

### Phase C — Draft the response plan

For each open comment, decide ONE of three responses:

| Response | When to use | What you'll do |
|---|---|---|
| **ARGUE** | The code is intentionally written this way; reviewer misunderstood | Post a technical explanation as a reply |
| **ASK** | The reviewer's intent is unclear; need clarification before fixing | Post a question as a reply |
| **ACCEPT + FIX** | Reviewer is correct; the issue is real and fixable | Fix the code + post an acknowledgement reply |

### Phase D — Present the plan to the user (REQUIRED before executing anything)

Show the user a clear summary like this:

```
Here is my proposed response plan for PR #<N>:

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
[1] github.py:30 — 🐛 BUG (pagination)
    Decision: ACCEPT + FIX
    Reply:    "✅ Accepted — adding pagination loop, GitHub returns max 30 files by default."
    Fix:      Add while loop with per_page=100 in get_pr_files()

[2] reviewer.py:87 — ⚡ PERFORMANCE (truncation)
    Decision: ARGUE
    Reply:    "💬 The truncation at string level is intentional here because..."

[3] reviewer.py:100 — ⚠️ ERROR-HANDLING (StopIteration)
    Decision: ASK
    Reply:    "❓ Are you expecting this to fail under normal tool_choice=forced usage,
              or only at max-tokens exhaustion? Clarifying before fixing."
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Shall I proceed with this plan? You can:
- Say "yes" to execute all
- Say "skip [N]" to drop an item
- Say "change [N] to ARGUE/ASK/ACCEPT" to override a decision
- Say "no" to cancel
```

**Do not execute until the user explicitly approves.**

### Phase E — Execute on approval

Only after the user says yes (or a modified version):

1. Post replies to GitHub for each item:
```bash
gh api repos/ykita0224-work/hive-strategy/pulls/comments/<ID>/replies \
  --method POST \
  --field body="<reply text>"
```

2. Apply code fixes for ACCEPT items (edit the files directly in Cursor)

3. Stage and commit:
```bash
git add <changed files>
git commit -m "fix: address review comments — <brief summary>

Co-Authored-By: Claude"
```

4. Push:
```bash
git push
```

5. Report what was done and that CI will re-review.

## Human Override Commands

At any point during or after the debate:

```bash
# Override: argue against a specific comment
gh api repos/ykita0224-work/hive-strategy/pulls/comments/<ID>/replies \
  --method POST \
  --field body="💬 **[Override — ARGUE]** <your reason>"

# Override: accept a comment the agent argued away
gh api repos/ykita0224-work/hive-strategy/pulls/comments/<ID>/replies \
  --method POST \
  --field body="✅ **[Override — ACCEPT]** Fixing this — reviewer is correct."
```

## What NOT to do

- Do not post replies or push code until the user has approved the plan
- Do not argue just to avoid work — only argue when the code is genuinely correct
- Do not fix things the reviewer was wrong about — post an argument instead
- Do not make unrelated changes while fixing — one concern at a time
